daemia","Hypertension","Thrombocytopaenia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypersplenism is a condition where the spleen becomes overactive, leading to the excessive removal of blood cells from circulation. This can result in \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombocytopaenia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a low platelet count, due to increased sequestration and destruction of platelets in the spleen. \u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertension\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperlipidaemia\u003C/strong\u003E are not directly caused by hypersplenism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypersplenism can lead to thrombocytopaenia due to increased sequestration and destruction of blood cells in the spleen.","The spleen plays a role in filtering blood and removing old or damaged blood cells."],"references":["Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kapila V, Wehrle CJ, Tuma F. Physiology, Spleen. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537307/","Cesta MF. Normal structure, function, and histology of the spleen. Toxicol Pathol. 2006;34(5):455-65. doi: 10.1080/01926230600867743. PMID: 17067939."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14975"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T14:52:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T14:52:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7663"